values: A foray into photomanipulation, so that I would have an image for my podfic of flawedamythyst's Old Memories And Young Hopes...

Okay, so this isn't fanfic (gasp! blasphemy!).  But it is fannish, so it totally counts for being posted here.

So, the amazing created an idea of chocolates based off Sherlock series 1 (here), which was reblogged by .  Thus, I found it.  But I'm no chocolatier.  I am, however, a decent baker.  So, I decided to reinterpret these ideas as cupcakes (with redsharlach's permission).  And I've finished the first one - The Choc Blanket!



I'm going to quote some of RedSharlach's description:
"Enrobed in comforting orange, a shocking secret lies concealed. But don't giggle - it's a lime cream!"

This is a devil's food cupcake, that I cut open from the bottom and piped in lime-cream filling, and then topped with orange-tinted glaze.  The recipes are after the cut, if you're interested.



Devil's Food Cupcakes (Makes 24)

4 squares (1 oz each) unsweetened chocolate, melted
2 cups all-purpose flour
1 tsp baking soda
1/4 tsp salt
3/4 cup butter, softened
1 1/3 cup firmly packed light brown sugar
2 eggs
2 tsp vanilla extract
1 cup milk

Preheat the oven to 350 degrees.  Butter and flour 24 muffin tins (do not use papers if you are making filled cupcakes).

In a medium bowl, whisk together the dry ingredients and set aside.

In a large bowl, beat the butter until light and fluffy.  Add the sugar and beat together until fluffy and well-blended.  Reduce mixer speed to medium, and beat in eggs, one at a time.  Beat in chocolate and vanilla.  Reduce mixer speed to low.  Beat in 1/4 of flour mixture, followed by 1/4 of the milk.  Continue alternating dry ingredients and milk until everything is added, and mix just until blended.

Spoon the batter into the prepared muffin tins.

Bake until the tops of the cupcakes are firm and spongy, about 20 minutes.  Cool in the muffin tins on wire racks for 10 to 20 minutes.

Lime-Cream Filling:

1 1/2 ounces white chocolate squares (or 1/4 cup pieces)
1/4 cup and 1/2 cup whipping cream, separated
1 Tbsp sugar
2 Tbsp key lime liquor
2 envelopes Dream Whip

In the top of a double boiler, add the white chocolate, 1/4 cup of the cream, and the sugar.  Heat water in the bottom portion of the double boiler until it just starts to simmer.  Place the top of the double boiler over the water and melt the ingredients together, stirring occasionally, until mixture is smooth.  Stir in the liquor.

Remove top of double boiler and set aside, allowing it to cool for 15 minutes.

In a medium bowl, beat the remaining 1/2 cup whipping cream until stiff peaks form.  Fold the chocolate mixture into the whipped cream.  Pour in the packets of dream whip, mixing thoroughly on medium after each is added.  Beat mixture until thoroughly blended, then place mixture into the refrigerator to cool for 7-10 minutes.

Once cool, whip mixture until soft peaks form.

To prepare cupcakes for filling

If you have not yet done so, remove the cupcakes from the muffin tin.  With a sharp knife, cut a circle into the bottom of the cupcake, inserting the blade no more than half the depth of the cupcake.  This plug of cupcake can then be gently pried out with the blade of the knife.  This will leave a hollow in the cupcake.  Fill this with the lime cream filling (I find it easiest to pipe the filling in with a pastry bag, but it can also be spooned in if you are careful).  Take the plug that you popped out from the center of the cupcake and slice off the bottom 1/8".  This new plug is then put back on the bottom of your cupcake the seal it up.



Glaze

3 cups confectioner's sugar, sifted
4 1/2 - 5 Tbsp milk
Food colouring

In a bowl, mix together the sugar and 4 1/2 Tbsp of the milk with a spoon.  Add the extra 1/2 Tbsp if the mixture is too thick to stir.  add food colouring (I used 5 drops each of red and yellow) and mix well.

Spread the glaze on the cupcakes.  Note: this glaze will thicken if you let it sit, so if you want the enrobing effect shown, you need to frost immediately.

Serve and enjoy!

===================

I've been iconing again - it's been quite a long time.  But you can blame for her wonderful turn of phrase in her Sherlock fanfictions.  I'm putting these behind an LJ-cut, because a couple of them have very strong language.  If you want to use these, feel free - just please, credit where credit is due.  =)


The one that started it all, from her story "Feeding Sherlock":
    

And ever onward, these are from the story "Four Shame, Sherlock"...
    .

And finally, this I have to take the blame for...

I have a bad habit of writing down little fic bits - notes, quotes, and inspirations for fics.  This wouldn't be any sort of problem but that I end up with them scattered across 5 notebooks and random bits of paper.  So, I'm doing a little housecleaning by consolidating these.  This probably won't be all that interesting, frankly, but I need to be able to keep this stuff together. Good Omens: Underground (inspired by) I blame Voltaire.  Not the French philosopher, but goth musician.  Been listening to Almost Human just after finishing GO again, and while reading GO fanfics.  So, the song "Underground" gets in my head and stays, especially the lyrics "And in the darkness I can see / Your skin's the closest thing to Grace."  So obviously, since I'm writing, this inspired a scene, or a series of them.  Crowley buried six feet under in a pine box, covered in wards and sigils designed to keep the demonic power bound inside.  The only one who's likely to even notice his absence is Aziraphale, so the question arises as to whether the angel can find him, and most importantly find him before he goes mad. Lepidoptera? Crowley's been out of touch, standing Aziraphale up for some lunch or drinking or such.  So Az goes looking.  He finds the demon in his flat (or perhaps someplace public?  Someplace several stories up, like inside Big Ben or something?).  Crowley's been pinned to the wall, a spike through each of his wings, and another pinning him right through the middle like a lepidoptera in an entomology collection.  As Aziraphale pulls the spikes from Crowley's wings, they fall to the ground in a heap, severed from his back.  The important (and difficult) thing to work in is that the wings will heal.  Whoever did this wants Crowley to know it can happen at any time - they can do it again whenever they like. ***** Sherlock (BBC): Things in the Dark He leaves the curtains open enough to let in the street light at night.  He's not afraid of the darkness - don't be silly.  But he can't be alone in the darkness.  In the darkness - the true deep darkness of a moonless desert night - they come out of hiding.  He can't see them, of course.  But he hears the skittering, the occasional chitinous click.  and he can smell them - a unique combination of mould, desert dust, and the faintest whiff of something festering.  So he always makes sure there's at least a little light coming in. But then came the night of the storm, when all of Baker Street lost power.  And he discovered that there aren't any batteries in his torch, and that Sherlock doesn't have anything as practical as candles in the flat. A Mess of Emotions Unbelievable as it sounds, John Watson had never before fired a gun in anger.  Even in Afghanistan.  Sure, he'd shot people, but there was never time for any real emotion to it.  It was simply survival. I Upset Her? After living with Sherlock for a while, John Watson had come to the understanding that there were a few unshakable truths: Sherlock Holmes was not a freak so much as he was gifted, and Mycroft Holmes was a manipulative bastard.  [Sherlock was born an empath, and Mycroft learned to suppress his emotions out of concern and caring for his brother] Phantom Pain (inspired by) John is haunted by Sherlock, literally.  So he begins to take on some of Sherlock's cases, as Sherlock does the actual deducing.  But he has to be very careful about what he says, as nobody else can see or hear Sherlock. Poetry Note: given to Atlin Merrick for use in Minutiae Sherlock does not do anything as normal as sing in the shower.  But he does recite poetry.  (Xanadu - Coleridge, Ode to a Nightingale - Keats, or Jabberwocky - Carroll) Counting Murders The crow and the raven.  Murders and Unkindnesses.  Moriarty and Sherlock.  Similar, oh so very similar.  But having distinct and very important differences. The Jumper John's favorite jumper?  You know, the oatmeal one?  He knit it himself. Hate it When He's Right John's problem with Sherlock's reaction in TGG (during the Carl Powers case) is that Sherlock is actually right, and John doesn't want to admit it. Sherlock at Large The idea of Sherlock becoming a criminal is ridiculous.  Sherlock lives to prove he is cleverer than is opponents.  He's already proven this time and again against the police - why else would they continue to call him in?  So there's no challenge in becoming a criminal.  He'd be bored within a fortnight.  And John knows this. Aces "I told our parents I didn't want to sleep with women because it was easier than telling them I didn't want to sleep with anybody." Binary Cygnus X-1: a binary star system with a blue supergiant and a black hole orbiting a common midpoint. Do the stars feel this desire?  To sever ties, and drift free?  Of are they content to orbit one another until the end of time? ***** Random The same words in a different mouth can become completely new. "Are you alright?" "I was dreaming." "Bad dream?" [S]He made a small noise of disagreement.  "Not bad.  Dangerous." I don't think we were wrong to fight.  In truth, I don't think it was ever a choice, not really.  Better to fight back than to wait and be hunted down like an animal.  but it was incredibly naive to think we could win.  We thought we were the rebels fighting the evil empire, and we'd eventually win because we were the good guys.  Except life doesn't work like that.  We fought, and we died.  And it didn't change a damn thing.  (Inspired by the RPG Nightbane) ***** And that's it for this notebook.  I'll probably have a couple more posts with more such nonsense later.

Listen.  You know, I was all set to write a nice fluffy little story about Sherlock reciting poetry in the shower.  I'd even picked out the poem, Kubla Khan by Coleridge, and was going to try to work in a small passing reference to a computer programmer with a couch impossibly stuck halfway up the stairs to his flat.  Seriously, I was perfectly happy with that idea.  I mean, yeah, I can't write smut to save my soul, but I'm good with the PG romantic fluff stories, and I like them.  Then along you come, you horrid little vorpal bunny, strap my muse to a vest-full of Semtex, and tell me I'm going to write the kind of story I don't even like to read.  I don't like whumping characters that much, especially not characters that aren't even mine, and even more especially not characters I actually like.  And every time I sit down to try to write a way out of the situation they've found themselves in, it somehow just ends up worse!  So, I give up, I'll write your horrid little story, and post it.  And then you can either go away, or I will drop you in a pot of boiling water and make some hasenpfeffer for everyone. Sorry, had to get that out of my system.  I made the mistake of trying to complain to a couple of non-writing friends, whose advice was "If you don't like the storyline, write something different."  Supremely unhelpful.

Just a brief character study on John Watson, based on the idea that living with a man like Sherlock Holmes is bound to change a person. The title is the name of one of the rooms in the video game "Vagrant Story." I just liked how it sounded.

Sanctum: The Alchemist's Laboratory

John Watson was not what one would call a fanciful man. His speech was straightforward, not given to metaphor or hyperbole. This may have been due to a naturally stolid nature. Certainly, both his medical and military training reinforced this tendency. Both fields necessitated seeing things as they are, rather than how they might be, or how they should be. Whatsoever was the cause, by the time he moved into the flat on Baker Street, John was well set in his ways. But it seems that a life with Sherlock Holmes can cause changes in even the steadiest of natures.
It wasn't some huge revelation, nothing blatant; just a subtle shift in thought. Sherlock was so different from anyone he'd previously met, that he seemed to be something more than human. The word "alien" would drift across John's mind, but it didn't seem quite right. Despite his unwillingness to interact with most people in any polite fashion, he still seemed to fit within his environment. No, Sherlock wasn't alien; rather, he gave the impression of being one step removed from humanity. He brought to John's mind stories his mother hand told him (when he was still young enough for such things), tales of the Fair Folk, and of changelings left in cribs.
At first John didn't notice these flights of fancy, as they always seemed to center somehow around Sherlock. And Sherlock was far enough from normal that these imaginings seemed natural. But the shift was subtle, gradual, and undeniable. So it wasn't until coming home one day to an elaborate chemistry experiment in progress in the kitchen that John finally acknowledged how much his friend and companion had impacted his life. Looking at the kitchen table and seeing the vast array of bubbling beakers and flasks, and the twisted lengths of distillation tubing, John started imagining alembics and retorts, and wondered if Sherlock actually was trying to find the Philosopher's Stone. He let his mind wander that path for a moment. But Sherlock was too uninterested in money; he'd undoubtedly declare the ability to turn lead into gold as "dull." John could see Sherlock trying to gain immortality, but only so he could experiment with ever more creative ways to commit suicide. 'Nah,' John thought. Sherlock wasn't that impractical – he'd get far too bored with eternity stretching out before him.
As John was thinking about all of this, Sherlock returned to the kitchen to check on his experiment. Seeing him, John decided to have him on a bit. With a grin he asked, "So, figured out how to turn lead into gold yet?"
"Don't be ridiculous, John. Even I couldn't do that without a particle accelerator."
John was actually a bit surprised that Sherlock had not deleted any information he'd learned about ancient alchemy, and had apparently considered the possibility of using something like the Large Hadron Collider to transmute elements. Thinking about it, Sherlock seemed a little less rigorous in "deleting" extraneous information over the time John had known him. Seeing such a change in Sherlock (even if it was a small one) forced John to admit that he himself had also changed. Working with Sherlock required a bit more imagination than might be expected. Sherlock couldn't afford to focus only on what was in front of him. He also had to anticipate what someone was going to do. And this apparently sparked John's own imagination off, albeit in other directions. He shook his head at his own fancies. "Any clean mugs around that you haven't used for poisons or body parts, Sherlock? I'll make us a cuppa."

It's all fault. This picture wouldn't leave me alone until I wrote a drabble about it. So, of course, I'm now posting it. Just a short little 500-word drabble.
Oh, and of course, I don't own Sherlock Holmes or John Watson. They belong to Sir Arthur Conan Doyle (for the character concepts) and to BBC/Moffat/Gatiss (for the current incarnations). The hitmen are mine though.
Warnings: Um, drama? Could be read as friendship, or could be read as slash (if, like me, you have permanently-affixed slash goggles).
****************

It felt like they had run halfway across London, though John knew that wasn't really the case. Case. God. Never should have taken it on, John thinks. Because now they're on the wrong side of the Russian mafia, with not one, but two hitmen after them. Finally, Sherlock stops, and John leans up against a nearby wall, just trying to catch his breath. After a moment, Sherlock turns to face him, putting his hand on the wall and leaning in. John tilted his head back slightly, looking up at Sherlock. "You know, this wasn't how I was planning to spend my weekend off."
"Oh?" Sherlock asked. "Well, you may want to take that up with our pursuers."
John chuckled a bit. "Well, at least it isn't boring." He sobered again almost immediately, tilting his head down. The situation wasn't funny. The men after them were frighteningly good at what they did, and the odds of both he and Sherlock coming out of this alive were not looking good. 'No,' he thought. 'Stop thinking like that. Focus on getting through this.'
Sherlock leaned in closer, letting his hair fall forward as he looked down at John. "John, I-"
John raised his hand to Sherlock's chest and cut him off before he could say another word. "Don't. Just... don't." Because John knew Sherlock, and while he may not be a deductive genius, he knew exactly what the other man was about to say. And he couldn't stand to hear those words right now; it would make everything far too real, and far too absolute. And John suddenly remembered, in that gestalt way that sometimes happens, a mate of his on the front lines by the name of Mike Tanaka, and how, whenever he called his wife back home, he never rung off with "goodbye." He'd said it sounded too final, and felt like bad luck. And though Sherlock's aborted statement wouldn't have shared a single phoneme, it still would have rung in the air just like goodbye.
Looking up at Sherlock, he said, "Later. When we're both back at the flat. You can tell me then." And no matter how foolishly optimistic that thought was, John clung to it. There would be a later, they would both have many more evenings at the flat on Baker Street. He stood up straight, like the soldier he'd probably always be, determined to see this through.
"Alright, John. At the flat." Then Sherlock smiled, and got that particular gleam in his eyes; and John knew he was about to suggest something dangerous, something more than a bit mad, something that would somehow have the best chance of getting them both out of this more-or-less intact. "This little game's been fun, but I think it's about time for the checkmate. Agreed?"
Sherlock's smile called forth one of John's own. He reached back to where he'd tucked his Browning, making sure it was in the best position for an easy draw. He nodded once, and said,"Agreed."

This is the journal I will be using to store my fanfiction.  This may cause cross-posting in a few places, as I may post things at the <lj comm="gw_safehouse"> for my GW stuff.  But, this is for everything, not just GW.  So, forewarned is forearmed.  To explain the setup, each post will have the Story Title and (if necessary) Chapter number and name in the subject line.  There will be a summary including warnings, pairings (where appropriate), and rating.  The rating is based on the standard MPAA guidelines for movies.  If this changes, you will see a post in regards to that.  Okay, thanks for paying attention.
